label-size4      = 10\n|label-color4      = black\n| mark-coord4      = {{coord|45.0879|-63.4019}}\n|mark-title4       = [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label5      = Enfield\n|       mark5      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size5       = 8\n|  label-pos5      = left\n| label-size5      = 10\n|label-color5      = black\n| mark-coord5      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title5       = [[Enfield, Nova Scotia]]\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18|10|26 p.m.}} \u2013 <br> {{end date|2020|4|19|11|26 a.m.}} [[Atlantic Daylight Time|ADT]]\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree killer|Spree shooting]], [[mass murder]],<ref name=\"Vox\" /> [[arson]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = 23<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> (including the perpetrator)<ref name=\"CBC10\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/portapique-shooting-memorials-april-21-1.5539894|title=22 victims confirmed dead in N.S. mass shooting|publisher=CBC News|first=Taryn|last=Grant|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| injuries         = 2<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--><ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Unknown (under investigation)\n}}\nOver a thirteen-hour period spanning April 18\u201319, 2020, a [[killing spree]] took place at various locations in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]]. Gabriel Wortman, a 51-year-old man, killed 22<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people and set fire to five buildings before the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) killed him.<ref name=\"CBC10\"/><ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=22 victims of N.S. rampage include retirees, pregnant health care worker, veteran|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is the deadliest rampage in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob |publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The RCMP has yet to establish a motive.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n===April 18===\nBeginning at around 10:26 p.m., several residents of the rural beachside community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], called [[9-1-1]] to report gunshots and several fires.<ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020 |publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=CBC News|first=|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-new-details-timeline-nova-scotia-manhunt-1.5541561|title=RCMP give new details on timeline of manhunt for N.S. shooter|date=April 22, 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020  |publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead in Nova Scotia shooting, Canadian authorities say|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=NBC News|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim}}</ref> [[ABC News]], citing unnamed investigators, reported that the incident may have begun as a case of [[domestic violence]] at a house where Wortman was trying to find a former partner.<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\"ABC2\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/death-toll-nova-scotia-shooting-rampage-increases-19/story?id=70251470|title=Nova Scotia shooting may have begun as a domestic violence dispute: Investigators|publisher=ABC News|last1=Deliso|first1=Meredith|last2=Pereira|first2=Ivan|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA source told [[CNN]] that Wortman burned down his own house before going to his former partner's residence, where he killed people living there and also nearby.<ref name=\"CNN\" /> When RCMP officers arrived on the scene twelve minutes later, at around 10:38 p.m., three houses on Portapique Beach Road and Orchard Beach Drive were found burning. Thirteen victims were soon located, who had reportedly been shot after fleeing the fires. One of the first officers to respond to the scene reported by radio that they could not locate an armed suspect and that \"it's very bad what's going on down here\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/nova-scotia-tick-tock-murder-rampage-1.5539000|title='Those scars will never heal': piecing together a gunman's murderous rampage in Nova Scotia|date=April 20, 2020 |publisher=CBC News|access-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC9\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/nova-scotia-shooting-manhunt-details-1.5542025|title='They don't know if they've caught him': Recordings reveal chaos of Nova Scotia manhunt|publisher=CBC News|last=Gatehouse|first=Jonathon|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last1=Mercer |first1=Greg |last2=Jones |first2=Lindsay |last3=Pruden |first3=Jana |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-shooter-acted-alone-during-rampage-rcmp-say/|title=RCMP defend not sending emergency alert before Nova Scotia gunman was killed |date=2020-04-23|access-date=2020-04-23|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423151005/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-shooter-acted-alone-during-rampage-rcmp-say/|archive-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nConfusion persisted for hours over whether a suspect had been apprehended.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /> At 11:32 p.m., the RCMP posted a [[Twitter|tweet]] asking residents of the area to stay inside with their doors locked and officers set up a search perimeter in the Portapique area. As the investigation developed overnight, they determined that the suspect had eluded them.<ref name=\":4\" /> By the morning of April 19, they said they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=MassLive}}</ref>\n\n===April 19===\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported an explosion and gunfire at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. The two residents were killed, as was a neighbour who went to render assistance. Another victim was then shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road back south to Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\" />\n\nRCMP identified Gabriel Wortman as the suspect at 8:54 a.m., and warned that he was impersonating a police officer by wearing an RCMP uniform and driving a replica police vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shah|first=Maryam|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=Global News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last1=Neustaeter|first1=Brooklyn|last2=Lopez-Martinez|first2=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CTV News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Between 10:04 and 11:04 a.m., he was seen in or near the communities of [[Glenholme, Nova Scotia|Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Onslow, Nova Scotia|Onslow]], and [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], indicating that he was travelling toward Halifax.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-timeline-of-nova-scotia-mass-shooting/|title=Timeline of Nova Scotia mass shooting|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|publisher=Globe and Mail}}</ref> At 10:54 a.m., surveillance video apparently captured Wortman pulling into a parking lot in [[Millbrook 27|Millbrook First Nation]] in the mock police vehicle, briefly getting out to put on a reflective vest, and then driving off.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Boynton|first=Sean|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6855907/nova-scotia-mass-shooting-new-video/|title=Video appears to show Nova Scotia shooting suspect stop, change clothes amid killing spree|date=April 22, 2020|work=Global News|access-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>During this time, Wortman performed three [[Traffic stop|traffic stops]] on random cars and killed their occupants.<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\nAt approximately 11:15 a.m., RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson encountered Wortman oncoming on [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2|Route 2]] in the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]], and rammed her cruiser into his replica to stop it.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/20/nova-scotia-shooting-details-emerge-in-gabriel-wortmans-rampage/|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Details emerge in suspect Gabriel Wortman's rampage|last=Sheehy|first=Kate|date=April 20, 2020|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421083535/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|archive-date=April 21, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Witnesses reported that Wortman exited his vehicle and shot into Stevenson's, killing her and injuring another officer.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /> Both cars also caught fire, though accounts differ as to when and how.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /> Wortman then stole a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[Sport utility vehicle|SUV]] from a nearby motorist, and was next seen continuing south along [[Nova Scotia Highway 102|Highway 102]] through [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]] at 11:24 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThirteen hours after police began pursuing him, at 11:26 a.m., Wortman was finally intercepted, shot, and killed by at least one officer at the [[Irving Oil#Big Stops|Irving Big Stop]] [[Rest area|service area]] in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /> His death was confirmed by police at 11:40 a.m.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Sean|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=Vox}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Victims==\nWortman killed 22<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people, including Constable Heidi Stevenson. He shot another officer, who survived.<ref name=\"CBC10\" /><ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\">{{Cite news|last=Quon|first=Alexander|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes}}</ref> One other person was injured.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> Victims were found in the communities of Portapique, Wentworth, Debert, Shubenacadie/Milford and Enfield.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52376547|title=Canada shooting: Death toll in Nova Scotia rises to 22|publisher=BBC News|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422000411/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52376547|archive-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The dead are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" />\n\nNames and photos of 14 victims were published in the ''[[National Post]]'' on April 21. According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of Wortman's first victims were closely connected to him, but as he continued, those he attacked became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' reported that Wortman had created a list of people to target, although not all those on the list were attacked.<ref name=\":5\" /> The newspaper noted that the two victims at the home in Wentworth were known to Wortman because one had previously gone hunting with him.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==Perpetrator==\n [[File:Atlantic Denture Clinic (3).jpg|thumb|Workers removing the signage from Atlantic Denture Clinic at 193 Portland St, Dartmouth Nova Scotia. Taken on April 22nd 2020.]]\n\nThe RCMP identified the perpetrator as Gabriel Wortman, a 51-year-old [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer, his [[yearbook]] entry alluding to this.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020|last=Frisko|first=Bruce}}</ref> Acquaintances described him as a polite and [[Wiktionary:house-proud#English|house-proud]] man who often spent time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman pleaded guilty to assault in 2002 and was sentenced to nine months of probation, in which he was prohibited from possessing weapons and ordered to undergo anger management counselling.<ref name=\"CTV6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/n-s-rcmp-say-they-were-in-process-of-preparing-alert-when-gunman-was-killed-1.4906672|title=N.S. RCMP say they were 'in process' of preparing alert when gunman was killed|publisher=CTV News|last=Flanagan|first=Ryan|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC8\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-criminal-record-1.5541176|title=Suspect in N.S. killings didn't have criminal record, but previously pleaded guilty to a crime|publisher=CBC News|last=Donkin|first=Karissa|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> He was also involved in two civil matters regarding property disputes, according to interviews and public records. A former acquaintance described how, in 2004, Wortman offered to help him when he had financial difficulties and was about to lose his house, only for Wortman to discreetly take ownership of the home away from him, evict him, and sell the property. In 2015, Wortman had been temporarily loaned a Portapique home a paternal uncle had purchased while he was in the process of selling his [[Edmonton]] condominium. Wortman refused to release the Portapique property back to him, claiming he was owed money, until the uncle eventually sold it.<ref name=\"CBC8\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6846920/nova-scotia-killer-financial-practices/|title='He stole my house': Nova Scotia killer had history of dubious financial practices|publisher=Global News|last1=Bell|first1=Stewart|last2=Russell|first2=Andrew|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman had a hobby of buying law enforcement [[memorabilia]] and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called his home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his denture clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with alcohol use and his business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFollowing the killings, the decorative signage on Wortman's denture clinic in Dartmouth, portraying a large smile and a set of dentures, garnered complaints from the public. In response, [[Halifax Regional Police]] removed the signage on April 22.<ref name=\"signage\">{{cite news |last1=April |first1=Allan |title=Police remove teeth, signage from denture clinic owned by N.S. shooter |url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/police-remove-teeth-signage-from-denture-clinic-owned-by-n-s-shooter-1.4907452 |publisher=CTV News |date=April 22, 2020 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Investigations==\n===Criminal===\nNo motive has been established for the killings, though they are not considered an act of [[terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nWortman's alleged list of targets was recovered from one of his properties. One person on the list, who was ultimately not a victim, had previously declined to sell Wortman a used police car.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citynews1130.com/2020/04/23/would-be-victim-nova-scotia-gunman-list-report/|title=Would-be victim reveals Nova Scotia gunman had 'list of people to target': report - NEWS 1130|website=www.citynews1130.com|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> \n\nOn the afternoon of April 20, Chief Superintendent Leather said there were 16 crime scenes, including five structure fires, over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}. He said he expected the death toll to rise as these crime scenes are investigated.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nLeather noted that Wortman's use of a police cruiser and wearing a police uniform allowed him to help evade detection for a long time. Owning police vehicles or uniforms is not a crime, but [[Police impersonation|impersonating a police officer]] is.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Donkin|first1=Karissa|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-shooting-rcmp-vehicle-1.5539877|title=Police uniform, mock RCMP cruiser key parts of investigation into N.S. shootings|date=April 21, 2020|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=April 22, 2020|last2=Daigle|first2=Thomas}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hill|first=Brian|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6851700/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-uniform-police-car|title=How a real uniform and replica police car helped the Nova Scotia gunman go undetected|date=April 22, 2020|work=[[Global News]]|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Leather also said that Wortman had no [[Possession and acquisition licence|licence to own guns]] and that his weapons were illegally purchased, which will be investigated further.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kelownanow.com/news/news/National_News/Police_have_good_idea_guns_used_in_Nova_Scotia_mass_shooting_were_not_licensed/|title=Police have \u2018good idea\u2019 guns used in Nova Scotia mass shooting were not licensed|last=KelownaNow|website=KelownaNow|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lamoureux|first=Mack|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/3a83av/nova-scotia-gunman-was-not-a-legal-firearms-owner-rcmp-says|title=Nova Scotia Gunman Was Not a Legal Firearms Owner, RCMP Says|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|publisher=Vice}}</ref>\n\nNova Scotia's [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would conduct an investigation into the shooting of Wortman, as well as another incident involving two RCMP officers who discharged their weapons inside a [[Fire station|fire hall]] in Onslow; Wortman was not there at the time.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|date=April 19, 2020|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the evening of April 21, the [[Canadian Armed Forces]] were dispatched to assist the RCMP in their investigation by providing them with additional personnel and supplies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/military-equipment-nova-scotia-rcmp-investigation-mass-killing-1.5540743|title=Military personnel, equipment to aid RCMP investigation into mass killing|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe Nova Scotia RCMP Major Crime Unit launched a tip hotline to gather further information about the attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/rcmp-launch-tip-line-to-gather-information-about-weekend-mass-shooting-1.4908807|title=RCMP launch tip line to gather information about weekend mass shooting|date=2020-04-23|website=Atlantic|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n===Use of emergency alert===\nFollowing questions about why Nova Scotia did not use [[Alert Ready]], Canada's emergency population warning system, to warn the public about the killings and instead used popular [[social media]] platforms Twitter and [[Facebook]] to provide updates, RCMP officials said they had been dealing with an unfolding situation and details kept being updated many times. However, the areas affected had poor cellular Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not have used Twitter. Relatives of the victims pointed out that Alert Ready would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors, which could have saved lives.<ref name=\"CTV7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/u-s-citizens-in-nova-scotia-were-sent-additional-warning-during-deadly-rampage-1.4907139|title=U.S. citizens in Nova Scotia were sent additional warning during deadly rampage|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cooke|first=Alex|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-shooting-emergency-alert-1.5540220|title='I would not have let my wife leave': Widower blasts lack of emergency alert during N.S. shootings|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/corrie-ellison-mass-shooting-brother-clinton-hiding-1.5541082|title=He was 'hunted' by the Portapique gunman and survived. His brother didn't|publisher=CBC News|last=Davie|first=Emma|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Chief Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process on alerting the public.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|last=Gorman|first=Michael|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421083535/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|archive-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC7\">{{cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/questions-remain-rcmp-ns-emergency-alert-1.5540100|title=Questions emerge about RCMP's failure to send emergency alert on gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, Leather said officers in Dartmouth were asked by the province about a warning at 10:15 am, but did not agree on details like wording before Wortman died 71 minutes later.<ref name=\"CTV6\" /> The [[List of diplomatic missions of the United States|United States Consulate]] in Halifax said it emailed American citizens in Nova Scotia warning them of the situation using the RCMP's information.<ref name=\"CTV7\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nFlags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|work=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420223029/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing |publisher=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200421002715/https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| archive-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Prime Minister of Canada|Canadian Prime Minister]] [[Justin Trudeau]] expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening [[gun control]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He asked the media to not use Wortman's name or image: \"Do not give this person the gift of infamy.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kktv.com/content/news/Police-At-least-10-killed-in-shooting-rampage-in-Canada-569772421.html|title=Canada's worst mass shooting leaves at least 18 dead|publisher=KKTV|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422085944/https://www.kktv.com/content/news/Police-At-least-10-killed-in-shooting-rampage-in-Canada-569772421.html|archive-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Elizabeth II]], [[monarchy of Canada|Queen of Canada]], expressed her condolences, saying that she and [[Prince Philip]] were \"saddened by the appalling events\", and that her thoughts and prayers were with the people of Nova Scotia and all Canadians. She also paid tribute to the \"bravery and sacrifice\" of the RCMP and other emergency services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-canada-crime-nova-scotia-britain/queen-elizabeth-sends-condolences-to-canada-after-nova-scotia-shooting-idUSKCN2231JF|title=Queen Elizabeth sends condolences to Canada after Nova Scotia shooting|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 21, 2020|publisher=Reuters|last=Faulconbridge|first=Guy}}</ref>\n\nThe [[White House]] condemned the killings and expressed US President [[Donald Trump]] and First Lady [[Melania Trump]]'s condolences.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/americas/nova-scotia-shooting-monday/index.html|title=Gunman evaded police for nearly 12 hours and killed at least 18 in one of Canada's deadliest mass shootings|publisher=CNN|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Eliott C.|last2=Newton|first2=Paula|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, the [[CN Tower]] was illuminated in blue and white, the colours of the [[Flag of Nova Scotia|Nova Scotia flag]], and also in RCMP red, blue, and gold in honour of Stevenson, on the quarter- and half-hours. On April 21, at [[Niagara Falls]], both the Canadian [[Horseshoe Falls]] and the [[American Falls]] were also illuminated in blue and white as a symbol of bi-national solidarity with Nova Scotia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/iconic-canadian-symbols-glow-blue-and-white-in-show-of-solidarity-with-nova-scotia-1.4907477|title=Iconic Canadian symbols glow blue and white in show of solidarity with Nova Scotia|publisher=CTV News|last1=Jerrett|first1=Andrea|last2=Price|first2=Melanie|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the days after the incident, many fundraisers for the victims and their families were started on the crowdfunding platform [[GoFundMe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/n-s-rampage-victims-young-sons-hid-during-attack-family-member-says-1.4906956 |title=N.S. rampage victims' young sons hid during attack, family member says |work=[[CTV News]] |last1=Neustaeter |first1=Brooklyn |date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC11\"/> There was also at least one fake or fraudulent fundraiser started, which was subsequently removed.  Jeff Thomson of the RCMP's Anti-Fraud Centre warned Canadians to be diligent when donating to charities related to the tragedy.<ref name=\"CBC11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/beware-of-fake-ns-shooting-charity-campaigns-rcmp-warns-1.5541570 |title=Fake N.S. shooting fundraiser leads to warning from RCMP |work=[[CBC News]] |last1=Colbert |first1=Yvonne |date=April 23, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs large gatherings are restricted in the province due to the coronavirus pandemic, a public virtual vigil is scheduled to air on CBC Atlantic on April 24 at 7:00 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|ADT]].<ref name=\"CBC12\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/virtual-vigil-facebook-22-victims-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5541093 |title=Virtual vigil honouring victims of N.S. shootings planned for Friday |work=[[CBC News]] |last1=CBC News |date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6852130/virtual-vigil-nova-scotia-shooting |title=How to watch the virtual vigil for the Nova Scotia shooting victims |work=[[Global News]] |last1=Goldfinger |first1=Daina |last2=Lieberman |first2=Caryn |date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n* [[List of rampage killers in the Americas]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/we-mourn-for-their-families-teacher-nurse-cancer-survivor-among-n-s-shooting-spree-victims-1.4903446 \"'We mourn for their families': Teacher, nurse, cancer survivor among N.S. shooting spree victims\"]. [[CTV News]]. April 20, 2020.\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{short description|Series of killings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size1       = 8\n|      label1      = Portapique\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.3972|-63.7067}}\n|  label-pos1      = left\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = [[Portapique, Nova Scotia]]\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n\n|      label2      = Wentworth\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|45.6564|-63.5493}}\n|mark-title2       = [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label3      = Debert\n|       mark3      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size3       = 8\n|  label-pos3      = right\n| label-size3      = 10\n|label-color3      = black\n| mark-coord3      = {{coord|45.4197|-63.4313}}\n|mark-title3       = [[Debert, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label4      = Shubenacadie\n|       mark4      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size4       = 8\n|  label-pos4      = left\n| label-size4      = 10\n|label-color4      = black\n| mark-coord4      = {{coord|45.0879|-63.4019}}\n|mark-title4       = [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label5      = Enfield\n|       mark5      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size5       = 8\n|  label-pos5      = left\n| label-size5      = 10\n|label-color5      = black\n| mark-coord5      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title5       = [[Enfield, Nova Scotia]]\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18|10|26 p.m.}} \u2013 <br> {{end date|2020|4|19|11|26 a.m.}} [[Atlantic Daylight Time|ADT]]\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree killer|Spree shooting]], [[mass murder]],<ref name=\"Vox\" /> [[arson]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = 23<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> (including the perpetrator)<ref name=\"CBC10\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/portapique-shooting-memorials-april-21-1.5539894|title=22 victims confirmed dead in N.S. mass shooting|publisher=CBC News|first=Taryn|last=Grant|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| injuries         = 2<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--><ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Unknown (under investigation)\n}}\nOver a thirteen-hour period spanning April 18\u201319, 2020, a [[killing spree]] took place at various locations in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]]. Gabriel Wortman, a 51-year-old man, killed 22<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people and set fire to five buildings before the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) killed him.<ref name=\"CBC10\"/><ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=22 victims of N.S. rampage include retirees, pregnant health care worker, veteran|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is the deadliest rampage in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob |publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The RCMP has yet to establish a motive.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n===April 18===\nBeginning at around 10:26 p.m., several residents of the rural beachside community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], called [[9-1-1]] to report gunshots and several fires.<ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020 |publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=CBC News|first=|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-new-details-timeline-nova-scotia-manhunt-1.5541561|title=RCMP give new details on timeline of manhunt for N.S. shooter|date=April 22, 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020  |publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead in Nova Scotia shooting, Canadian authorities say|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=NBC News|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim}}</ref> [[ABC News]], citing unnamed investigators, reported that the incident may have begun as a case of [[domestic violence]] at a house where Wortman was trying to find a former partner.<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\"ABC2\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/death-toll-nova-scotia-shooting-rampage-increases-19/story?id=70251470|title=Nova Scotia shooting may have begun as a domestic violence dispute: Investigators|publisher=ABC News|last1=Deliso|first1=Meredith|last2=Pereira|first2=Ivan|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA source told [[CNN]] that Wortman burned down his own house before going to his former partner's residence, where he killed people living there and also nearby.<ref name=\"CNN\" /> When RCMP officers arrived on the scene twelve minutes later, at around 10:38 p.m., three houses on Portapique Beach Road and Orchard Beach Drive were found burning. Thirteen victims were soon located, who had reportedly been shot after fleeing the fires. One of the first officers to respond to the scene reported by radio that they could not locate an armed suspect and that \"it's very bad what's going on down here\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/nova-scotia-tick-tock-murder-rampage-1.5539000|title='Those scars will never heal': piecing together a gunman's murderous rampage in Nova Scotia|date=April 20, 2020 |publisher=CBC News|access-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC9\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/nova-scotia-shooting-manhunt-details-1.5542025|title='They don't know if they've caught him': Recordings reveal chaos of Nova Scotia manhunt|publisher=CBC News|last=Gatehouse|first=Jonathon|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last1=Mercer |first2=Greg |last2=Jones |first2=Lindsay |last3=Pruden |first3=Jana |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-shooter-acted-alone-during-rampage-rcmp-say/|title=RCMP defend not sending emergency alert before Nova Scotia gunman was killed |date=2020-04-23|access-date=2020-04-23|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423151005/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-shooter-acted-alone-during-rampage-rcmp-say/|archive-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nConfusion persisted for hours over whether a suspect had been apprehended.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /> At 11:32 p.m., the RCMP posted a [[Twitter|tweet]] asking residents of the area to stay inside with their doors locked and officers set up a search perimeter in the Portapique area. As the investigation developed overnight, they determined that the suspect had eluded them.<ref name=\":4\" /> By the morning of April 19, they said they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=MassLive}}</ref>\n\n===April 19===\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported an explosion and gunfire at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. The two residents were killed, as was a neighbour who went to render assistance. Another victim was then shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road back south to Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\" />\n\nRCMP identified Gabriel Wortman as the suspect at 8:54 a.m., and warned that he was impersonating a police officer by wearing an RCMP uniform and driving a replica police vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shah|first=Maryam|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=Global News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last1=Neustaeter|first1=Brooklyn|last2=Lopez-Martinez|first2=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CTV News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Between 10:04 and 11:04 a.m., he was seen in or near the communities of [[Glenholme, Nova Scotia|Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Onslow, Nova Scotia|Onslow]], and [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], indicating that he was travelling toward Halifax.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-timeline-of-nova-scotia-mass-shooting/|title=Timeline of Nova Scotia mass shooting|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|publisher=Globe and Mail}}</ref> At 10:54 a.m., surveillance video apparently captured Wortman pulling into a parking lot in [[Millbrook 27|Millbrook First Nation]] in the mock police vehicle, briefly getting out to put on a reflective vest, and then driving off.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Boynton|first=Sean|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6855907/nova-scotia-mass-shooting-new-video/|title=Video appears to show Nova Scotia shooting suspect stop, change clothes amid killing spree|date=April 22, 2020|work=Global News|access-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>During this time, Wortman performed three [[Traffic stop|traffic stops]] on random cars and killed their occupants.<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\nAt approximately 11:15 a.m., RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson encountered Wortman oncoming on [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2|Route 2]] in the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]], and rammed her cruiser into his replica to stop it.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/20/nova-scotia-shooting-details-emerge-in-gabriel-wortmans-rampage/|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Details emerge in suspect Gabriel Wortman's rampage|last=Sheehy|first=Kate|date=April 20, 2020|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421083535/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|archive-date=April 21, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Witnesses reported that Wortman exited his vehicle and shot into Stevenson's, killing her and injuring another officer.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /> Both cars also caught fire, though accounts differ as to when and how.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /> Wortman then stole a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[Sport utility vehicle|SUV]] from a nearby motorist, and was next seen continuing south along [[Nova Scotia Highway 102|Highway 102]] through [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]] at 11:24 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThirteen hours after police began pursuing him, at 11:26 a.m., Wortman was finally intercepted, shot, and killed by at least one officer at the [[Irving Oil#Big Stops|Irving Big Stop]] [[Rest area|service area]] in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /> His death was confirmed by police at 11:40 a.m.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Sean|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=Vox}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Victims==\nWortman killed 22<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people, including Constable Heidi Stevenson. He shot another officer, who survived.<ref name=\"CBC10\" /><ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\">{{Cite news|last=Quon|first=Alexander|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes}}</ref> One other person was injured.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> Victims were found in the communities of Portapique, Wentworth, Debert, Shubenacadie/Milford and Enfield.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52376547|title=Canada shooting: Death toll in Nova Scotia rises to 22|publisher=BBC News|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422000411/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52376547|archive-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The dead are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" />\n\nNames and photos of 14 victims were published in the ''[[National Post]]'' on April 21. According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of Wortman's first victims were closely connected to him, but as he continued, those he attacked became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' reported that Wortman had created a list of people to target, although not all those on the list were attacked.<ref name=\":5\" /> The newspaper noted that the two victims at the home in Wentworth were known to Wortman because one had previously gone hunting with him.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==Perpetrator==\n [[File:Atlantic Denture Clinic (3).jpg|thumb|Workers removing the signage from Atlantic Denture Clinic at 193 Portland St, Dartmouth Nova Scotia. Taken on April 22nd 2020.]]\n\nThe RCMP identified the perpetrator as Gabriel Wortman, a 51-year-old [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer, his [[yearbook]] entry alluding to this.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020|last=Frisko|first=Bruce}}</ref> Acquaintances described him as a polite and [[Wiktionary:house-proud#English|house-proud]] man who often spent time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman pleaded guilty to assault in 2002 and was sentenced to nine months of probation, in which he was prohibited from possessing weapons and ordered to undergo anger management counselling.<ref name=\"CTV6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/n-s-rcmp-say-they-were-in-process-of-preparing-alert-when-gunman-was-killed-1.4906672|title=N.S. RCMP say they were 'in process' of preparing alert when gunman was killed|publisher=CTV News|last=Flanagan|first=Ryan|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC8\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-criminal-record-1.5541176|title=Suspect in N.S. killings didn't have criminal record, but previously pleaded guilty to a crime|publisher=CBC News|last=Donkin|first=Karissa|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> He was also involved in two civil matters regarding property disputes, according to interviews and public records. A former acquaintance described how, in 2004, Wortman offered to help him when he had financial difficulties and was about to lose his house, only for Wortman to discreetly take ownership of the home away from him, evict him, and sell the property. In 2015, Wortman had been temporarily loaned a Portapique home a paternal uncle had purchased while he was in the process of selling his [[Edmonton]] condominium. Wortman refused to release the Portapique property back to him, claiming he was owed money, until the uncle eventually sold it.<ref name=\"CBC8\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6846920/nova-scotia-killer-financial-practices/|title='He stole my house': Nova Scotia killer had history of dubious financial practices|publisher=Global News|last1=Bell|first1=Stewart|last2=Russell|first2=Andrew|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman had a hobby of buying law enforcement [[memorabilia]] and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called his home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his denture clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with alcohol use and his business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFollowing the killings, the decorative signage on Wortman's denture clinic in Dartmouth, portraying a large smile and a set of dentures, garnered complaints from the public. In response, [[Halifax Regional Police]] removed the signage on April 22.<ref name=\"signage\">{{cite news |last1=April |first1=Allan |title=Police remove teeth, signage from denture clinic owned by N.S. shooter |url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/police-remove-teeth-signage-from-denture-clinic-owned-by-n-s-shooter-1.4907452 |publisher=CTV News |date=April 22, 2020 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Investigations==\n===Criminal===\nNo motive has been established for the killings, though they are not considered an act of [[terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nWortman's alleged list of targets was recovered from one of his properties. One person on the list, who was ultimately not a victim, had previously declined to sell Wortman a used police car.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citynews1130.com/2020/04/23/would-be-victim-nova-scotia-gunman-list-report/|title=Would-be victim reveals Nova Scotia gunman had 'list of people to target': report - NEWS 1130|website=www.citynews1130.com|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> \n\nOn the afternoon of April 20, Chief Superintendent Leather said there were 16 crime scenes, including five structure fires, over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}. He said he expected the death toll to rise as these crime scenes are investigated.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nLeather noted that Wortman's use of a police cruiser and wearing a police uniform allowed him to help evade detection for a long time. Owning police vehicles or uniforms is not a crime, but [[Police impersonation|impersonating a police officer]] is.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Donkin|first1=Karissa|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-shooting-rcmp-vehicle-1.5539877|title=Police uniform, mock RCMP cruiser key parts of investigation into N.S. shootings|date=April 21, 2020|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=April 22, 2020|last2=Daigle|first2=Thomas}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hill|first=Brian|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6851700/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-uniform-police-car|title=How a real uniform and replica police car helped the Nova Scotia gunman go undetected|date=April 22, 2020|work=[[Global News]]|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Leather also said that Wortman had no [[Possession and acquisition licence|licence to own guns]] and that his weapons were illegally purchased, which will be investigated further.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kelownanow.com/news/news/National_News/Police_have_good_idea_guns_used_in_Nova_Scotia_mass_shooting_were_not_licensed/|title=Police have \u2018good idea\u2019 guns used in Nova Scotia mass shooting were not licensed|last=KelownaNow|website=KelownaNow|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lamoureux|first=Mack|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/3a83av/nova-scotia-gunman-was-not-a-legal-firearms-owner-rcmp-says|title=Nova Scotia Gunman Was Not a Legal Firearms Owner, RCMP Says|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|publisher=Vice}}</ref>\n\nNova Scotia's [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would conduct an investigation into the shooting of Wortman, as well as another incident involving two RCMP officers who discharged their weapons inside a [[Fire station|fire hall]] in Onslow; Wortman was not there at the time.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|date=April 19, 2020|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the evening of April 21, the [[Canadian Armed Forces]] were dispatched to assist the RCMP in their investigation by providing them with additional personnel and supplies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/military-equipment-nova-scotia-rcmp-investigation-mass-killing-1.5540743|title=Military personnel, equipment to aid RCMP investigation into mass killing|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe Nova Scotia RCMP Major Crime Unit launched a tip hotline to gather further information about the attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/rcmp-launch-tip-line-to-gather-information-about-weekend-mass-shooting-1.4908807|title=RCMP launch tip line to gather information about weekend mass shooting|date=2020-04-23|website=Atlantic|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n===Use of emergency alert===\nFollowing questions about why Nova Scotia did not use [[Alert Ready]], Canada's emergency population warning system, to warn the public about the killings and instead used popular [[social media]] platforms Twitter and [[Facebook]] to provide updates, RCMP officials said they had been dealing with an unfolding situation and details kept being updated many times. However, the areas affected had poor cellular Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not have used Twitter. Relatives of the victims pointed out that Alert Ready would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors, which could have saved lives.<ref name=\"CTV7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/u-s-citizens-in-nova-scotia-were-sent-additional-warning-during-deadly-rampage-1.4907139|title=U.S. citizens in Nova Scotia were sent additional warning during deadly rampage|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cooke|first=Alex|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-shooting-emergency-alert-1.5540220|title='I would not have let my wife leave': Widower blasts lack of emergency alert during N.S. shootings|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/corrie-ellison-mass-shooting-brother-clinton-hiding-1.5541082|title=He was 'hunted' by the Portapique gunman and survived. His brother didn't|publisher=CBC News|last=Davie|first=Emma|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Chief Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process on alerting the public.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|last=Gorman|first=Michael|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421083535/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|archive-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC7\">{{cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/questions-remain-rcmp-ns-emergency-alert-1.5540100|title=Questions emerge about RCMP's failure to send emergency alert on gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, Leather said officers in Dartmouth were asked by the province about a warning at 10:15 am, but did not agree on details like wording before Wortman died 71 minutes later.<ref name=\"CTV6\" /> The [[List of diplomatic missions of the United States|United States Consulate]] in Halifax said it emailed American citizens in Nova Scotia warning them of the situation using the RCMP's information.<ref name=\"CTV7\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nFlags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|work=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420223029/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing |publisher=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200421002715/https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| archive-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Prime Minister of Canada|Canadian Prime Minister]] [[Justin Trudeau]] expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening [[gun control]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He asked the media to not use Wortman's name or image: \"Do not give this person the gift of infamy.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kktv.com/content/news/Police-At-least-10-killed-in-shooting-rampage-in-Canada-569772421.html|title=Canada's worst mass shooting leaves at least 18 dead|publisher=KKTV|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422085944/https://www.kktv.com/content/news/Police-At-least-10-killed-in-shooting-rampage-in-Canada-569772421.html|archive-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Elizabeth II]], [[monarchy of Canada|Queen of Canada]], expressed her condolences, saying that she and [[Prince Philip]] were \"saddened by the appalling events\", and that her thoughts and prayers were with the people of Nova Scotia and all Canadians. She also paid tribute to the \"bravery and sacrifice\" of the RCMP and other emergency services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-canada-crime-nova-scotia-britain/queen-elizabeth-sends-condolences-to-canada-after-nova-scotia-shooting-idUSKCN2231JF|title=Queen Elizabeth sends condolences to Canada after Nova Scotia shooting|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 21, 2020|publisher=Reuters|last=Faulconbridge|first=Guy}}</ref>\n\nThe [[White House]] condemned the killings and expressed US President [[Donald Trump]] and First Lady [[Melania Trump]]'s condolences.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/americas/nova-scotia-shooting-monday/index.html|title=Gunman evaded police for nearly 12 hours and killed at least 18 in one of Canada's deadliest mass shootings|publisher=CNN|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Eliott C.|last2=Newton|first2=Paula|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, the [[CN Tower]] was illuminated in blue and white, the colours of the [[Flag of Nova Scotia|Nova Scotia flag]], and also in RCMP red, blue, and gold in honour of Stevenson, on the quarter- and half-hours. On April 21, at [[Niagara Falls]], both the Canadian [[Horseshoe Falls]] and the [[American Falls]] were also illuminated in blue and white as a symbol of bi-national solidarity with Nova Scotia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/iconic-canadian-symbols-glow-blue-and-white-in-show-of-solidarity-with-nova-scotia-1.4907477|title=Iconic Canadian symbols glow blue and white in show of solidarity with Nova Scotia|publisher=CTV News|last1=Jerrett|first1=Andrea|last2=Price|first2=Melanie|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the days after the incident, many fundraisers for the victims and their families were started on the crowdfunding platform [[GoFundMe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/n-s-rampage-victims-young-sons-hid-during-attack-family-member-says-1.4906956 |title=N.S. rampage victims' young sons hid during attack, family member says |work=[[CTV News]] |last1=Neustaeter |first1=Brooklyn |date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC11\"/> There was also at least one fake or fraudulent fundraiser started, which was subsequently removed.  Jeff Thomson of the RCMP's Anti-Fraud Centre warned Canadians to be diligent when donating to charities related to the tragedy.<ref name=\"CBC11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/beware-of-fake-ns-shooting-charity-campaigns-rcmp-warns-1.5541570 |title=Fake N.S. shooting fundraiser leads to warning from RCMP |work=[[CBC News]] |last1=Colbert |first1=Yvonne |date=April 23, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs large gatherings are restricted in the province due to the coronavirus pandemic, a public virtual vigil is scheduled to air on CBC Atlantic on April 24 at 7:00 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|ADT]].<ref name=\"CBC12\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/virtual-vigil-facebook-22-victims-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5541093 |title=Virtual vigil honouring victims of N.S. shootings planned for Friday |work=[[CBC News]] |last1=CBC News |date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6852130/virtual-vigil-nova-scotia-shooting |title=How to watch the virtual vigil for the Nova Scotia shooting victims |work=[[Global News]] |last1=Goldfinger |first1=Daina |last2=Lieberman |first2=Caryn |date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n* [[List of rampage killers in the Americas]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/we-mourn-for-their-families-teacher-nurse-cancer-survivor-among-n-s-shooting-spree-victims-1.4903446 \"'We mourn for their families': Teacher, nurse, cancer survivor among N.S. shooting spree victims\"]. [[CTV News]]. April 20, 2020.\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Davemck", "label": "safe", "comment": "Clean upduplicate template argumentsusingfindargdups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Scotia_killings"}
